<a href=3D"https://calcresource.com/geom-hexagon.html#anchor-16">See also</=
a></div></div><a name=3D"anchor-3"></a><h3>Definitions</h3><p>Hexagon is a =
polygon with six sides and six vertices. Like any polygon, a hexagon can be=
 either convex or concave, as illustrated in the next figure. When convex, =
a hexagon (or a polygon in general) has none of its interior angles greater=
 than 180=C2=B0. To the contrary, a concave hexagon (or polygon) has one or=
 more of its interior angles greater than 180=C2=B0. <strong>A hexagon is c=
alled regular when all of its sides and interior angles are equal</strong>.=
 Unlike the triangle, having the sides equal does not imply that the interi=
or angles are also equal, since the hexagon may be concave. As demonstrated=
 in the figure below, many possible concave hexagons can be defined, with e=
qual sides, but unequal interior angles (these are called equilateral). Any=
 hexagon that is not regular is called irregular.</p><figure class=3D"image=
"><img src=3D"https://cdn.calcresource.com/images/geom-hexagon-regular.rev.=
4cd9ee7ce1.png" loading=3D"lazy" height=3D"400" width=3D"332"><figcaption>T=
ypes of hexagons</figcaption></figure><p>The sum of the internal angles of =
any hexagon, either convex or concave is always 720=C2=B0. This can be easi=
ly be concluded by counting the number of triangles fitting inside the hexa=
gon, by connecting its vertices (avoiding intersections). Indeed, there are=
 4 triangles. Since he sum of internal angles in one triangle is 180=C2=B0,=
 4 triangles, side by side, should measure up to 4x180=3D720=C2=B0.</p><fig=
ure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://cdn.calcresource.com/images/geom-he=
xagon-triangles.rev.3b91b88638.png" loading=3D"lazy" height=3D"109" width=
=3D"204"><figcaption>The diagonals of a hexagon separate its interior into =
4 triangles</figcaption></figure><a name=3D"anchor-4"></a><h3>Properties of=
 regular hexagons</h3><a name=3D"anchor-5"></a><h4>Symmetry</h4><p>The regu=
lar hexagon features six axes of symmetry. Half of them are passing through=
 diagonally opposite vertices and the remaining through the middles of oppo=
site edges.</p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://cdn.calcresource=
.com/images/geom-hexagon-symmetry.rev.56a1a02cb2.png" loading=3D"lazy" heig=
ht=3D"279" width=3D"279"><figcaption>Axes of symmetry of a regular hexagon<=
/figcaption></figure><div class=3D"adplace" name=3D"AD_PARAGRAPH"></div><a =
name=3D"anchor-6"></a><h4>Interior angle and central angle</h4><p>Regular p=
olygons have equal interior angles by definition. Since there are six of th=
em in total, it can be concluded that each interior angle of a regular hexa=
gon is equal to:</p><p><span class=3D"mjpage mjpage__block"><svg xmlns:xlin=
k=3D"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width=3D"17.636ex" height=3D"5.343ex" st=
yle=3D"vertical-align: -1.838ex; margin-left: 3.484ex;" viewBox=3D"0 -1508.=
9 7593.4 2300.3" role=3D"img" focusable=3D"false" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.or=
g/2000/svg" aria-labelledby=3D"MathJax-SVG-1-Title">
<title id=3D"MathJax-SVG-1-Title">\varphi=3D{720^\circ\over 6}=3D120^\circ<=
/title>
