ce.com/images/geom-hexagon-angles.rev.45088f27de.png" loading=3D"lazy" heig=
ht=3D"241" width=3D"271"></figure><div class=3D"messageBox informMsg"><span=
 class=3D"icon"><img src=3D"https://cdn.calcresource.com/images/no-icon.rev=
.51610a34e3.png" alt=3D"icon" class=3D"icon-info-icon"></span><p>The regula=
r hexagon is composed by six identical equilateral triangles having a commo=
n vertex, the polygon centre.</p></div><a name=3D"anchor-7"></a><h4>Circumc=
ircle and incircle</h4><p>As happens with any regular polygon, a circle tha=
t passes through all six vertices of the hexagon can be drawn. This is the =
cirmuscribed circle or <strong>circumcircle </strong>of the polygon.&nbsp;T=
he center of this circle is the center of the hexagon. Likewise, the diagon=
als of the hexagon are diameters of the circumcircle. The radius of circumc=
ircle <span class=3D"mjpage"><svg xmlns:xlink=3D"http://www.w3.org/1999/xli=
nk" width=3D"2.708ex" height=3D"2.509ex" style=3D"vertical-align: -0.671ex;=
" viewBox=3D"0 -791.3 1166 1080.4" role=3D"img" focusable=3D"false" xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-labelledby=3D"MathJax-SVG-6-Title">
<title id=3D"MathJax-SVG-6-Title">R_c</title>
<g stroke=3D"currentColor" fill=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"0" transfo=
rm=3D"matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)" aria-hidden=3D"true">
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-52" x=3D"0" y=3D"0"></use>
 <use transform=3D"scale(0.707)" xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-63" x=3D"1074" y=3D=
"-213"></use>
</g>
</svg></span> is usually called circumradius.</p><p>Another circle can also=
 be drawn, that passes through the middles of the hexagon sides. This circl=
e is called inscribed circle or <strong>incircle</strong>. It is tangent to=
 all six sides and its center coincides with the center of the circumcircle=
. The radius of incircle <span class=3D"mjpage"><svg xmlns:xlink=3D"http://=
www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width=3D"2.564ex" height=3D"2.509ex" style=3D"vertic=
al-align: -0.671ex;" viewBox=3D"0 -791.3 1103.8 1080.4" role=3D"img" focusa=
ble=3D"false" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-labelledby=3D"MathJ=
ax-SVG-7-Title">
<title id=3D"MathJax-SVG-7-Title">R_i</title>
<g stroke=3D"currentColor" fill=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"0" transfo=
rm=3D"matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)" aria-hidden=3D"true">
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-52" x=3D"0" y=3D"0"></use>
 <use transform=3D"scale(0.707)" xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-69" x=3D"1074" y=3D=
"-213"></use>
</g>
</svg></span> is usually called inradius.</p><figure class=3D"image"><img s=
rc=3D"https://cdn.calcresource.com/images/geom-hexagon-circles.rev.039af343=
50.png" loading=3D"lazy" height=3D"251" width=3D"241"><figcaption>Circumscr=
ibed and inscribed circles of regular hexagon</figcaption></figure><p>The r=
adius of circumcircle <span class=3D"mjpage"><svg xmlns:xlink=3D"http://www=
.w3.org/1999/xlink" width=3D"2.708ex" height=3D"2.509ex" style=3D"vertical-=
align: -0.671ex;" viewBox=3D"0 -791.3 1166 1080.4" role=3D"img" focusable=
=3D"false" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-labelledby=3D"MathJax-=
SVG-8-Title">
