8ex" height=3D"1.676ex" style=3D"vertical-align: -0.338ex;" viewBox=3D"0 -5=
76.1 640.5 721.6" role=3D"img" focusable=3D"false" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.o=
rg/2000/svg" aria-labelledby=3D"MathJax-SVG-39-Title">
<title id=3D"MathJax-SVG-39-Title">\alpha</title>
<g stroke=3D"currentColor" fill=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"0" transfo=
rm=3D"matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)" aria-hidden=3D"true">
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-3B1" x=3D"0" y=3D"0"></use>
</g>
</svg></span>, using only a ruler and a compass. Follow the steps described=
 below:</p><ol><li>First just draw a linear segment whose length is the des=
ired hexagon side length <span class=3D"mjpage"><svg xmlns:xlink=3D"http://=
www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width=3D"1.488ex" height=3D"1.676ex" style=3D"vertic=
al-align: -0.338ex;" viewBox=3D"0 -576.1 640.5 721.6" role=3D"img" focusabl=
e=3D"false" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-labelledby=3D"MathJax=
-SVG-40-Title">
<title id=3D"MathJax-SVG-40-Title">\alpha</title>
<g stroke=3D"currentColor" fill=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"0" transfo=
rm=3D"matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 0)" aria-hidden=3D"true">
 <use xlink:href=3D"#MJMATHI-3B1" x=3D"0" y=3D"0"></use>
</g>
</svg></span>.</li><li>Then construct a circle, having its center at one en=
d of the linear segment and radius equal to the segment length.</li><li>Wit=
hout changing the radius, construct a second circle, having its center at t=
he other end of the linear segment. Two points are defined where this circl=
e intersects with the first one.</li><li>Using the same radius, place the t=
ip of the compass on either one of the lastly defined points and construct =
a new circle. A new point is defined at the intersection with the first cir=
cle.</li><li>Repeat the same procedure two more times. Place the tip of the=
 compass on the last point and construct a new circle. A new point is defin=
ed at the intersection with the first circle.</li><li>Six points have been =
defined so far around the first circle. These are the vertices of the hexag=
on. Draw linear segments between them and the regular hexagon is now comple=
te. The initial circle is the circumcircle of the hexagon.</li></ol><p>The =
following figure illustrates the drawing procedure step by step.</p><figure=
